dataIdInfo.idAbs: National boundary shapefile of Ghana for joining (linking) to population estimates provided in a table prepared by the U.S. Census Bureau.
dataIdInfo.idPurp: The U.S. Census Bureau is providing annual subnational five-year age group population estimates by sex for 2000 to 2020 in a geographic information system (GIS) for users of the Spatial Data Repository, funded by the U.S. President’s Emergency Plan for AIDS Relief (PEPFAR).
dataIdInfo.idCredit:
CENSUS DATA
(1) 2000 Population and Housing Census Data Analysis Report Volume 2, Appendix A 7.I: District Population Densities. Ghana Statistical Service. Available online at http://www.statsghana.gov.gh/nada/index.php/catalog/3 (accessed January 29, 2018). (2) 2010 Population and Housing Census, District Analytical Report(s), Table 2.1: Population by age, sex and type of locality. Ghana Statistical Service. Available online at http://www.statsghana.gov.gh/DistrictReport.html (accessed January 29, 2018). The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of non-U.S. census and survey data.
SHAPEFILE
International boundaries coincide with the Large Scale International Boundaries (LSIB) dataset from the U.S. Department of State, Office of the Geographer and Global Issues. Available online at http://geonode.state.gov (accessed 2018). Geospatial data for the national boundary of Ghana were provided by George Washington University, Department of Geography and International Affairs (February 02, 2017). The U.S. Census Bureau cannot guarantee the accuracy of boundary placements.
NATIONAL ESTIMATES AND PROJECTIONS
U.S. Census Bureau, Population Division. INTERNATIONAL DATA BASE, August 2017 release, available at https://www.census.gov/data-tools/demo/idb/informationGateway.php, accessed in August 2017.
NATIONAL AND SUBNATIONAL AREA NAMES AND CODES
(1) U.S. National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency. NGA GEOnet Names Server (GNS), available at http://geonames.nga.mil/gns/html/, accessed in September 2017. For geographic area names from the U.S. Board on Geographic Names and the U.S. Government Federal Information Processing System (FIPS) codes. (2) U.S. Government Geopolitical Entities, Names, and Codes (GENC) Standard. NSG Standards Registry, available at https://nsgreg.nga.mil/genc/discovery, accessed in February 2018.

Consts.useLimit:
U.S. Census Bureau population estimates: None. Acknowledgment of the Census Bureau would be appreciated in products derived from its population estimates.

The subnational boundaries used for this shapefile were shared with the U.S. Census Bureau to be made public for this product. The international boundaries are derived from the Large Scale International Boundaries (LSIB) dataset (public domain).

dataIdInfo.suppInfo:
The shapefile contains 1 polygon representing Ghana's national boundary.
FEATURE AND ATTRIBUTE DETAILS
The 2000-2020 population estimates for Ghana's administrative divisions are provided in the following 2 tables: The Unicode tab-delimited text file (table) "Ghana_5yr_age_sex_2000-2020_uscb_sep2018.txt," which can be joined to the shapefile via the common field "GEO_MATCH." The Excel table "Ghana_5yr_age_sex_2000-2020_508_uscb_sep2018.xlsx," formatted for accessibility in compliance with Section 508 of the U.S. Government's Federal Rehabilitation Act.
Details on processing of the census data and calculation of 2000-2020 estimates are provided in the "Census_Metadata" tab of the Excel file and "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas" document.
For the subnational areas, the U.S. Board on Geographic Names (BGN) "approved" names from the NGA GEOnet Names Server (cited in the "Credits") were used. For any area that a BGN name was not available, the name from the national census was used. Official codes for the subnational areas from the country's national statistical office, when available, are entered in the "NSO_CODE" field in both the text and Excel tables. Information on any alternative area names or recent name or boundary changes is entered in the "USCBCMNT" field.
A partial list of the fields in the Excel and Unicode text files, including all fields identifying geographic names and codes, is provided in the Excel file's "Data_Dictionary" tab.
ADDITIONAL INFORMATION
More detail on the U.S. Census Bureau subnational age and sex group estimates and maps for PEPFAR can be found in the document "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." It includes a data dictionary that is similar to that in the Excel table.
ACCESS
The U.S. Census Bureau’s products for PEPFAR can be accessed from the SPATIAL DATA REPOSITORY:
Zipped file containing geographic boundary data, tables with subnational population estimates, and instructions for linking (joining) the text file to the geographic boundary data: http://spatialdata.dhsprogram.com/home/. This web address also provides access to data and maps from the DHS (Demographic and Health Surveys) Program.
Instructions for linking (joining) the text file to the geographic boundary data can also be found in a standalone methodology document in the Spatial Data Repository.
For more information, see the following methodology documents in the Spatial Data Repository: (1) "Subnational Population Estimates Components for the Spatial Data Repository." (2) "Methods for Calculating 5-Year Age Group Population Estimates by Sex for Subnational Areas."
All of the above documents, tables, and geographic boundary data (zipped) are also available at the "Subnational Population by Sex, Age, and Geographic Area" page on https://www.census.gov.
